{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1vuillard_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604574/1945081401/0126.xml":{"full_text":"UP Will Study Tape\nFor Clue to False\nSurrender 'Flash'\nEj the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Aug. 14.\u2014The United\nPress said last night it had or\ndered impounded all teletype tape\nat all points along the circuit over\nwhich was sent a false \u201cflash\u201d Sun\nday night that Japan had sur\nrendered.\nThe UP said it hoped that a\nstudy of the tape \u201cwould provide a\nclue to the identity of the guilty\nperson\u201d sending the erroneous in\nformation. A reward of $5,000 was\noflered by Hugh Baillie, United\nPress president, for the identifica\ntion and conviction of the person\nsending the report.\nLacks Equipment.\nThe UP said the American\nTelephone Telegraph Co. from\nwhich it leases its news wires, re\nported that its investigation dis\nclosed that the flash did not orig\ninate in any of its test stations.\nThe A. T. T. said it had filed\na similar report with the Federal\nCommunications Commission, which\nhad requested a report.\nThe A. T. T. statement said\nthe flash could not have originated\nin any of its test stations because\n\u201cthe flash was transmitted by auto\nmatic tape and these test stations\nare not equipped with the equipment\nto perforate tape.\u201d\nAP Reward Proposed.\nKent Cooper, general manager of\nthe Associated Press, made the fol\nlowing statement:\n\u201cIt is to the interest of the public,\nof the newspapers and radio and of\nthe press associations that there be\nno tampering with the facilities of\nthe press associations, or any manip\nulation by which the press associa\ntions are imposed upon through the\nunauthorized use of their channels\nof information for the transmission\nof fraudulent news. I deeply regret\nthat anything of this kind has been\nexperienced by the United Press\nAssociation.\n\u201cIt is imperative that the integ\nrity of the news reports of the press\nassociations be protected against\nfraud. I hope, therefore, that the\nboard of directors of the Associated\nPress will add an appropriate\namount to the reward offered by the\nUnited Press Association for the ap\nprehension and conviction of any\none who is guilty of the incident of\nfraud as reported by that news\nagency.\n\u201cThere is a law against tampering\nwith wires in interstate commerce\nand I hope the Federal Communica\ntions and the Federal Bureau of In\nvestigation will undertake their in\nvestigations and that they will be j\nsuccessful.\u201d\nCommittee to Go to Moscow\nLONDON, Aug. 14 </P>.\u2014Russian!\nvisas were received today by mem-1\nbers of a House Appropriations'\nCommittee now. touring Europe\nchecking American diplomatic facil\nities as a preliminary to possible re-!\nvisions. The House group will be i\nflown from Berlin to Moscow.\nFalse Murder\nReport Sends 12\nPolice to Scene\nA 41-year-old colored man ac\ncused of falsely reporting a murder\nto bring police to his home during\na domestic argument Saturday night\ngot the surprise of his life when no\nless than 12 officers appeared, he\ntestified today in Municipal Court.\n\u201cI thought one scout car would\ncome,\u201d Nathaniel White, 2008 L\nstreet N.W., told the court. \u201cI\ndidn't know a bunch like that was\ncoming up.\u201d\nJudge Aubrey Fennell suspended\na sentence of a $50 fine or 60 days\nin jail and put the defendant on a\nyear\u2019s probation after learning he\nis the father of 10 children. White\nsaid he had been drinking and had\nbeen arguing with his wife, Cecelia,\nwhen the latter threatened to call\npolice. He then told her he would\ncall officers himself, he said.\n\u201cI didn\u2019t tell them a murder had\nbeen committed,\u201d he testified. \u201cI\njust said there may be murder.\u201d\nPolice headquarters telephone\noperator, Viola Resser, however,\ntestified White told her \"they are\nmurder here!\u201d The call resulted in\narrival at the scene within a few\nminutes of a headquarters crui^r\ncar and three patrol cruisers, two\nmotorcycles, a patrol wagon and a\nhomicide squad car, police said.\n_LOST.\nBICYCLE, boy\u2019s, blue and white. Reward\nif returned to MRS. CHARLES MARTON.\n\u2022M01 Arundel rd.. Apt. 2. Mt. Rainier, Md.\nBILLFOLD, leather, lady's, in Hot Shoppe,\nSilver Spring. Monday eve.. Aug. 13; cont.\nmoney, driver's permit, soc. sec. card,\nothers. Reward. GE, 6045, _*\nBILLFOLD, lady's, Monday a m., in Post\nOffice at 7th and F n.w,, or Hecht\u2019s; con\ntains Md. and D. C. permits, other cards.\nCg\u00bbl R, B,, TR. 8303. Reward.14\u00bb\nBLACK SUEDE BAG, contents billfold. $80.\nfountain pen. glasses, keys, with name and\naddress on ring, compact, lipstick, black\nsuede gloves; lost Saturday night. Re-\nward, LI, 5571. 1330 E st. n.e, 14\u201c\nBLAZER JACKET, lady's, navy blue: vie.\ndowntown F. G and 13th sts.. Sat. eve\nnlng; retvard. TA. 9033.\nBRACELET, in vicinity of College Park: 1\nAustralian coin. Sentimental value. Re\nward. UN. 3493. 1\nBROOCH, platinum, enamel and diamonds,\nBritish Royal Tank Corps crest, Sunday\na m., vie. Washington Canoe Club, Potomac\nRiver. Great sentimental value. Crest,\nregiment of veteran husband killed in ac\ntion. Reward. RE. 6700, Ext. 5779.\nCAMERA, Argus. Mt. Vernon, Monday; lib-\neral reward. Family film important to\nowner. 2116 No. Nottingham. Arlington.\nCL. 1347.\nEYEGLASSE8. pink shell, blue case, in cab i\nor vie. 23rd and C n.w. to 14th and Irving\nn.w. Reward. HO. 747!t. ,1\nEYEGLASSES, bifocal, downtown section, 1\nFriday night. 1504 Lawrence st. n.e. i\nLIFETIME PARKER PEN, gray and gold,\nIn case. Reward. Glebe 5536 after 6 p.m. 1\nFIN. AKA Sorority, lost in Zoo or on\nCathode University bus, on Sunday, August\n12, Taylor 7615__\u2022\nFOCKETBOOK, woman\u2019s, lost Saturday bet.\n11 and 12 a.m.. containing money. 2 ration I\nbooks, keys. Belongs to elderly lady\u2014she f\nneeds it. Reward. HO. 1116.\n!aOCS\u00abT?<OOK\u2019 *?rown leather, containing\nIdentification card, money, personal papers, i\nReward. Telephone RE. 7400, Ext 7288\n_14* 1\nFUBSE, black leather, containing money,\nlost in or near National City Christian\nChurch or on Mass. ave. Sunday Cali TE\n2038._ _\nSILVER BRACELET with square green 1\natones, lcinity Irving st. P. o., 14th and\nPark rd. Reward. GE. 6892.\nSKIRT, lady's, tan, on Cabin John street-\ncar. Reward. Call WI. 6228 after 6 p.m. i\nWALLET* brown leather, no money, cards, I\nchecks, receipts, etc.: urgently needed by\nowner. Liberal reward. SL. 4236.\nWALLET, containing money, pictures, gas 1\nratlonstamps, permit. Reward. Call\nFR. 0636 after 5 p.m., MANILLA SMITH.\nWALLET, containing Dilot\u2019s license: lost in\ncab; reward. MIES FORBES, 3726 Conn I\nave. DU, 5100, EM, 9213._\nWOULD THE MAN driving \"Moonshine\nDaughter, a '38 Chrysler, between Bev- 1\nerly Beach and Washington, call DU. 1649, 1\nalter 5;30?\nWRIST WATCH, man\u2019s, yellow gold, \"Ham- 1\nfjton.\" on U st. or Fla. ave. car. Initials 1\nW, H. W,\"; sentimental. AD. 0115. 16\u00ab\nWRIST .WATCH* \u2018VPaunam,\u201d yellow gold,\nwith 2 diamonds; lost on Glover Park bus.\ncIllUORy:i073nttm<!DU1 y,1Ue~ Regtrd'\nFOUND\nFOR LOST AND WANTED DOGS, phone 1\nSL 5183 MONTGOMERY COUNTY ANI\nMAL SHELTER.\nSUM OF MONEY, found In Safeway, \u201clath f\nVd JL_I.i(ave. n.e. Telephone WA. 8710 1\nYOUNG FEMALE DOG, part collie. ~Cali\nTempi* 1615. l\nSAN FRANCISCO CELEBRATES WITH BONFIRE\u2014Jubilant citizens mill around a bonfire started In the middle of San Fran\ncisco\u2019s busy Market street early today after newspaper headlines read: \"Tokyo Radio Says Japs Quit.\u201d Sidewalk War Bond\nbooths were fuel for the fire, which was extinguished with difficulty. \u2014AP Wirephoto.\nReconversion Delays\nWill Extend Jobless\nPeriod, Green Says\nEy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, Aug. 14.\u2014William\nGreen, president of the American\nFederation of Labor, says the AFL\nfeels \u201cthe Government is poorly\nprepared to meet the issue of re\nconversion.\u201d\nHe said there was \u201cmuch evidence\nof governmental delay on the issue\u201d\nand \u201cif manufacturers are not giv\nen the green light, we are appre\nhensive that the expected period of\nunemployment will be extended.\u201d\nMr. Green made the remarks in a\nstatement issued after a meeting of\nthe AFL Executive Council yester\nday.\nA Cincinnati stovemaker, he said,\ntried to purchase machinery to\nmake stoves before the end of the\nwar. The manufacturer, Mr. Green\nsaid, reported his request had been\nj turned over to the Justice Depart\nment for checking \u201cfor evidence of\n\u2018monopoly.\u2019\nI \u201cI presume,\" Mr. Green con\nj tinued, \u201ccases like that have hap\npened all over the country. Em\nj ployers should have been given a\nchance to prepare for postwar\nj manufacture. If they had been\ni given priorities for civilian produc\nj tion, unemployment could have\nj been minimized.\u201d\nThe council announced adoption\nof a four-point program for return\ning veterans.\nPoints called for establishment\nby all AFL central labor councils of\nspecial committees to help veterans\nfind jobs, employer-union agree\nments providing for training and\nemployment of veterans \u201con a fair\nand equitable basis, accumulated\nseniority for the time veterans were\nin service and support of legislation\n\u201cto accord veterans full opportun\nities for education and training, to\nassist them to buy homes or to start\nin business and to provide them\nwith the highest practical stand\nards of unemployment compensa\ntion.\u201d\nHillman Sees 10 Million\nOut of Jobs in Eight Weeks\nNEW YORK. Aug. 14 WP).\u2014Sidney!\nHillman, chairman of the Cio!\nPolitical Action Committee, says\n\u201cprobably about 10 million people\u201d\nwill be unemployed in six to eight\nweeks.\n\u201cWe are in quite the same kind\nof emergency as in 1933,\u201d Mr. Hill\nman said at a press conference\nyesterday.\nHe announced a national CIO\neducational campaign for a 65-cent\nhourly minimum wage and $25\nweekly unemployment compensa\ntion.\nThe CIO program also seeks\npassage of the Murra.v-Patman full\nemployment bill, the Murray-Wag\nner-Dingell bill for health insur\nance, establishment of a permanent\nFair Employment Practice Commit\ntee and a national housing program,\nhe said.\nReconversion\n(Continued From First Page.)\nsubject said wage controls might be\neased somewhat in the near future,\nbut that no radical revision of the\nLittle Steel wage formula is likely.\nThey said employers and workers\nmight be allowed to negotiate wage\nincreases in cases where the adjust\nments wouldn\u2019t lead to price rises.\nThe Little Steel formula holds basic\nwage rates to 15 per cent above\nJanuary, 1941, levels.\nAid for Plants Authorised.\n4. War Production Board Chair\nman King announced a program\nembracing use of priorities assist\nance to speed expansion of indus\ntrial plant facilities. He said the\npurpose of the step was to \u201cgive em\nployment to workers as fast as they\nare released from war production.\u201d\nThe WPB chief emphasized, how\never, that no general, overall priori\nties assistance will be granted.\nRather, priorities will be limited to\nitems which cannot otherwise be\nobtained.\nMr. Krug also served notice on in\ndustry that WPB regulations gov\nerning inventories would be strictly\nenforced, both before and after\nV-J day. He said immediate steps\nwould oe taken to see that \u201cwide\nscale civilian production is not im\npeded by excessive stockpiling, pre\nemptive buying or hoarding of\nscarce materials by a few.\u201d\nDr. Taylor voiced his strike pre\ndictions in an interview after a visit\nto the White House yesterday. Say\ning \u201cit took a big Nation of big\npeople to accomplish what we have\nin this war,\u201d the WLB chairman\nadded: \u201cI can\u2019t think that we will\nchange overnight.\n\u201cThere probably will be \u00ab\u00abnf\nstrikes. There probably will be some\nworkers who think their uniim is\nbeing threatened, or some employer\nwho thinks he has an unbearable\nproblem\u2014but I am confident there\nwill be no wave or rash of strikes.\u201d\nOne labor, leader, asking that he\nnot be named, gave this view: 4\n\u201cEven without the war to keep\nmen on the job, there will be strong\nforces to head off strikes. They are:\nManagement\u2019s desire to make a\nquick conversion to peacetime pro\nduction without difficulties, and the\nworker\u2019s desire to hold down a job\nin a loosening labor market.\u201d\nAmplifying their predictions con\ncerning unemployment, the Govern\nment economists presented this gen\neral outlook:\nWithin two months after V-J day,\n5.000. 000 munitions workers will lose\ntheir jobs. (This was estimated last\nweek by War Manpower Commission\nofficials.)\nMany of those won\u2019t be classified\nas \"unemployed\u201d because they won\u2019t\nbe looking for other jobs. Also,\nmany quickly will get other jobs.\nOn the other hand, when 5,000,000\nworkers in munitions plants are\nout, a large number of other work\ners will be out too, because of \u201csec\nondary effects.\u201d For example, peo\nple working in restaurants near the\nclosed plants.\nChangeover to Take Time.\nOn top of this, the armed forces\nwill step up their discharges. Vet\nerans will be pouring back on the\nscene.\nIt will take some time for most\nwar plants to get ready for peace\ntime production. Although many\ncivilian jobs are open, the released\nwar workers are not always in the\nright place to take them, and trans\nportation troubles won't clear up\nright away.\nNext year, many of the unem\nployed should be able to get to the\nright place at the right time and\ntake civilian jobs. But next year\nmore millions of veterans will be\ncoming home from the war\u2014enough\nto raise the 7,000,000 perhaps to\n9.000. 000 before the trend is re\nversed.\nIf unemployment reaches 9,000,\n000 it will be just about where it\nstood at the beginning of the de\nfense program in 1940, the econo\nmists said.\nSocial Security\n(Continued From First Page!\nmust be increased by appropriation\nfrom general taxation.\nAt present, 4,250,000 persons are\nreceiving social security benefits\ntotalling $111,000,000 a month, the\nboard reported.\nThe text of Mr. Truman\u2019s state\nment:\n\u201cIn a world still at war It Is well\nI that we pause to celebrate one of the\ni great peacetime achievements of\nthe American people, namely, the\nj enactment of the Social Security\nj Act. It is only 10 years ago that\njthis act became law. Yet in this\n1 brief period of time social security\nhas become an essential part of the\nAmerican way of life.\n\u201cWe have a right to be proud of\nthe progress we have already made\nin this field. We have a national\nsystem of old-age and survivors\u2019 in\nsurance under which 40,000,000\nworkers are insured, not only for\nold-age annuities but also for\nmonthly benefits to their wives,\nchildren, and dependent parents in\ncase of the worker\u2019s death. Already\nthere are well over 1,000,000 bene\nficiaries actually receiving monthly\nchecks under this insurance sys\ntem.\nUnemployment Insurance.\n\u201cWe have a Nation-wide unem\nployment insurance system brought\nabout by Federal action but admin\nistered by the States, under which\n36,000,000 workers are provided some\nprotection against wage loss due to\n-involuntary unemployment.\n\u201cWe have provided Federal grants\nin-aid to the States to enable them\nto pay cash assistance to the needv\naged, the needy blind, and de\npendent children. Today 2,750,000\nmen, women and children are re\nceiving thi^ assistance. In addi\ntion, there are other provisions of\nthe Social Security Act which pro\nmote child welfare and nubile\nhealth.\n\u201cBut while we have made prog\nress we still have a long way to go\nbefore we can truthfully say that\nour social security system furnished\nthe people of this country adequate\nprotection. Therefore, we should\nlose no time in making of our Social\nSecurity Act a more perfect instru\ni i\nTruman to Give Honor Medal\nTo Yank Who Risked Own Fire\nBr the Associated Pres*.\nPresident Truman personally will\npresent the Congressional Medal of\nHonor to T/Sergt. Peter J. Dalesson\ndro, who, risking death, called for\na mortar barrage on his own posi\ntion to halt a German attack.\nThe 27-year-old former truck\ndriver of Watervliet, N. Y., was cap\ntured during the action but now\nhas returned to this country. The\nWar Department announced the\nhonor award yesterday.\nHe previously had won the Silver\nStar for gallantry and the Purple\nHeart.\nSergt. Dalessondro, a member of\nthe 9th Infantry Division, with his\nplatoon, on last December 22 was\nholding off German forces near\nKalterherberg, Germany. During\nthe early morning the first German\nment for the maintenance of eco\nnomic security throughout this\ncountry.\n\u201cI expect to present to the Con\ngress specific recommendations\nlooking toward this objective.\n\"A sound system of social security\nrequires careful consideration and\npreparation. Social security worthy\nof the name is not a dole or a device\nfor giving everybody something for\nnothing. True social security must\nconsist of rights which are earned\nrights\u2014guaranteed by the law of\nthe land. Only that kind of social\nsecurity is worthy of the men and\nwomen who have fought and are\nnow fighting to preserve the heri\ntage and the future of America.\u201d\n_\nAtlanta Journal Names\nWright Bryan Editor\nBy the Associated Press.\nATLANTA, Aug. 14. Wright\nBryan, associate editor and man\naging editor of the Atlanta Journal,\nwho recently returned from\nEurope where he served as war\ncorrespondent, has been named edi\ntor of the Journal.\nHe succeeds John Paschall, who\nbecomes editor emeritus.\nW. S. Kirkpatrick, assistant man\naging editor, was promoted to man\naging editor.\nThe promotions were announced\nlast night by John A. Brice, presi\ndent of the Journal Co., at a dinner\nat which editorial workers of the\nnewspaper assembled to welcome\nMr, Bryan home.\nMr. Paschall, a member of the\nJournal staff since 1901, has been\neditor for the last she and a half\nyears after previously serving as\nreporter, city editor, managing edi\ntor and associated editor of the\nJournal.\nMr. Bryan was shot and captured\nby Germans in September, 1944.\nHe was released by the Russians\nfrom Oflag 64 in Poland in Janu\nary this year and taken to Paris\nfor medical treatment. He returned\nto Atlanta in July.\nSocial Security Expansion\nUrged by Welfare Group\nBy thf Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, Aug. 14.\u2014Uncertain\nties of the post V-J day reconver\nsion period \"make it doubly impor\ntant\u201d that social security benefits\napply to all workers in the Nation\nwith as great uniformity as possible,\nLoula Dunn, president of the Amer\nican Public Welfare Association, said\nyesterday.\nMiss Dunn said in a statement\nthat America's social insurance pro\ngram \"will effectively cushion the\nshock of a sudden shift from war to\npeace production,\u201d but added there\nare large groups of workers, includ\ning Federal employes, agricultural\nworkers, domestic help and the self\nemployed, \u201cwho still need to be\nbrought under this program if they\nare to avoid the relief rolls.\u201d\nI\nI\nST. PATRICK\u2019S CHURCH\n10th and G Sts. N.W.\nSOLEMN CEREMONY\nOF THANKSGIVING\n7:30 P.M. on day when victory is\nOFFICIALLY ANNOUNCED\nThe Apostolic Delegate will officiate\nTe Deum by the choir of the Theological College.\n\nattack threatened to overwhelm the\nplatoon. Sergt. Dalessondro, mov\ning up to an advanced observation\npost, directed mortar fire, used his\nown rifle and kept encouraging his\nmen until they repelled the enemy.\nLater in the day, the Germans\nlaunched a second attack. Once\nagain, the citation said, Sergt.\nDalessondro rushed to the observa\ntion post and called for mortar fire.\nAfter exhausting the ammunition\nfor his own rifle, he crawled 30 yards\nover open ground to get a light\nmachine gun, returned to his posi\ntion and fired at the Germans at\nvirtually point-blank range until the\ngun jammed. The citation added:\n\"As the German hordes swarmed\nabout him, he was last heard calling\nfor a barrage, saying, \u2018OK mortars,\nlet me have it\u2014right on this posi\ntion.\u2019\nFleet\n(Continued From First Page.)\nright up to takeoff times as repairs\non more and more planes were\nrushed to completion.\nGreatest Super Fortresses strike\nof the war was on August 1-2 by\n820 planes observing Army Air\nForces day.\nToday\u2019s attacks began with a\nstrike against the Marifu railway\nyards on Honshu shortly after noon.\nThese yards are only 14 miles south\nwest of Hiroshima, which was 60\nper cent destroyed by the first atomic\nbomb dropped on Japan.\nRailway Shops Blasted.\nAs the reports came trickling in,\nthese targets were added to the list:\nRailway shops near Iwakuna, just\nsouth of Hiroshima; shipping off\nKure naval base; the great Hikari\nnaval arsenal near Tokuyama, and\nthe Osaka army arsenal, Japans\nlargest. In addition, harbor mining\ncontinued.\nThe bombing, at altitudes from\n15,000 to 20,000 feet in clear weather\nwas described as having '\"consid\nerable effect\u201d by pilots who made\npreliminary reports by radio while\nstill over the targets.\nNo fighter opposition had been re\nported, and antiaircraft fire was\nmeager.\nFighters Attack Airfields.\nFor a half-hour before the Osaka\nraid and for 20 minutes afterward,\nMustangs and Thunderbolts from\nIwo swept over Osaka airfields.\nOther fighters escorted the B-29s.\nIwakuni had -been warned by a\nleaflet raid on August 5 that it was\non the Super Fortress \u201cdeath list.\u201d\nIt, Marifu and Hikari had not been\nraided before, but the Osaka area\nhad been struck hard and repeat\nedly.\nMuch of the city of Osaka had\nbeen razed by previous fire raids\nand 19 per cent of the Osaka arsenal\nhad been destroyed prior to today\u2019s\nblow.\nHikari, Japan\u2019s second-largest re\nmaining naval arsenal, covers an\narea of 28,000,000 square feet. It is\n50 miles southeast of Tokuyama and\n37 miles southwest of Kure.\nMarifu has a 10-track yard, 3,000\nfeet long, on a main line running\nfrom Tokyo southward. Smashing\nit would hamper shipments of food\nand supplies to the capital.\nDust Storm in Kansas\nHUTCHINSON, Kans., Aug. 14 (A5).\n\u2014An old-fashioned dust storm\nreminiscent of the \u201cDust Bowl\u201d days,\nrolled across Central Kansas from\nthe west yesterday afternoon. Visi\nbility here was cut to a block for\nthe 15 minutes\u2019 duration of the dust,\nwhich was followed by a heavy rain.\nrtsCl\n1 REP MBS I\nFREE ESTtMATt\nwhu rw i\nI given on the tl\nX d]\u00b0 baSS\u00ab\u00bb*WePticf t\nsuss? 1\nSTcamr*\"\u2019 I\nty. to xl\n1\nXI\n5HHHIR\n2 Senate Committees\nSchedule Hearings to\nSpeed Postwar Bills\n\u00a37 tht Associated Press.\nTwo Senate committees have\nscheduled hearings on postwar em\nployment problems as the first defi\nnite move toward reconvening Con\ngress early next month.\nA banking subcommittee will re\nsume hearings a week from today\non a sweeping economic measure\ncalled by its authors \u201cthe full em\nployment bill.\u201d The Finance Com\nmittee is expected to meet August\n39 on expansion of the unemploy\nment compensation system with\nmaximum benefits of $25 a week\nfor 26 weeks.\nCongress itself will convene prob\nably on September 4 or 5, Senate\nMajority Leader Barkley has an\nnounced. The plan is to process\nthe most needed pieces of legislation\nthrough committees before that time.\nThen the lawmakers could begin\nconsidering them on the floor, imme\ndiately on their return from their\ncurtailed vacation. The recess origi\nnally had been slated to last until\nOctober 8.\nCommittee action had not been\nscheduled today on three other legis\nlative items Senator Barkley put on\nhis high-priority list.\nThose include bills to authorize\nthe President to reorganize the\nExecutive Department, to create a\nsurplus property disposal system\nheaded by one man, rather than a\nboard as at present, and considera\ntion of which wartime boards and\nagencies should be abolished and\nwhich continued, when peace re\nturns.\nOWI Magazine Printed\nIn France to Be Sold\nBy the Associated Press.\nVoir, an illustrated fortnightly\nmagazine published in France by the\nOffice of War Information, has been\ndeclared surplus and will be offered\nfor sale.\nOWI said today Voir had been\nturned over to the Army and Navy\nLiquidation Commission for disposal\nunder Surplus Property Board regu\nlations.\nOriginally, OWI intended to sus\npend the magazine with the issue\nof September 15, but the Surplus\nProperty Board took the position\nthat it was a \u201cproperty,\u201d and there\nfore should be disposed of as such.\nWhat is being offered for sale\nactually consists chiefly of the name.\nOWI owns no publishing facilities\nin France, the magazine having been\npublished in French-owned plants.\nOWI explained the magazine was\nstarted as a temporary operation to\nsupply information to the French\nafter liberation. Since then many\nFrench publications have resumed\noperations.\nVoir, which sold for about 20 cents\na copy, had total sales exceeding\n$1,000,000. This money went into the\nUnited States Treasury. However,\nthere has not been an accounting to\ndetermine how much of this was\nprofit.\nSimon E. Smith, Employe\nAt Fort Washington, Dies\nSimon E. Smith, 53, employed as\na carpenter at Fort Washington,\ndied today at Mount Alto Hospital\nafter an illness of two weeks.\nMr. Smith, a veteran of the World\nWar, was a member of the Amer\nican Legion and the Veterans of\nForeign Wars.\nBom in Everett, Pa., he lived in\nAltoona, Pa., before coming to\nWashington several years ago. He\nlived at 2369 Rhode Island avenue\nN.E. here.\nHe is survived by his widow, Mrs.\nBertha L. Smith; two sons, Pvt.\nRichard E. Smith, who is with an\nArmy radio unit at Vint Hill Farm,\nWarrenton, Va., and Corpl. Robert\nE. Smith, who is expected home\nsoon from duty with the 701st Tank\nDestroyer Battalion in Italy, and\nhis father, Lewis Smith of Everett.\nFuneral services and burial will\nbe in Altoona.\nCuban Theaters Close\nIn Protesting Decree\nBy the Associated Press.\nHAVANA, Aug. 14.\u2014A decree by\nPresident Ramon Grau San Martin\nobliging movie theaters to include\nin their programs acts performed\nby musicians and actors resulted\nlast night in more than 100 movie\nhouses closing in protest.\nMONEY I\nI\n\u2014is not always 1\nmoney put aside,\nunspent. Some-\ntimes it is money I\ngained by a timely I\n\u2018\u2018buy,\u201d a home, for\ninstance. fl\nA home loan here I\nrequires the least\npossible \u201cred tape,\u201d I\nand may save you I\nmoney in lower in- Ij\nterest on the sum 1\nyou need. There\nare money saving I\nadvantages in com- I\ning to I\nH\nColumbia I\nFEDERAL I\nSAVINGS b LOAN I\nASSOCIATION 1\n716 11th St N.W. 1\nNA. 6543 I\nJaps Had Peace Plan,\nIncluding Suicide for\nLeaders, Chinese Say\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHUNGKING, Aug. 11 (Delayed).\n\u2014The Chinese Army newspaper Sao\nTang Po said today Japan was ready\nto offer up her war leaders as hara\nkiri victims and retreat to her 1931\nboundaries as conditions of peace,\neven before the first atomic bomb\nfell and Russia entered the Pacific\nWar.\nQuoting Hsieh Nan Kuang, de\nscribed as a leader of the Formosan\nRevolutionary League, the newspaper\npictured the growth of a surrender\nclique in Tokyo as fire bombs and\nexplosives fell on Japan\u2019s cities and\nAmerican carrier planes struck her\nfleet.\nIt described the Empress Nagako\nas a peace plan organizer.\nHere is the newspaper\u2019s account\nof Hsieh\u2019s report:\nThe first step toward peace was\ntaken June 3 by Imperial Household\nMinister Tsuneo Matsudaira, busi\nness manager for the imperial fam\nily and its fortune, which has been\nestimated at 4 per cent of all the\nwealth in Japan.\nMatsuidaira resigned, with the\naim of organizing a pro-American,\npro-British surrender cabinet. The\nplan failed because of the army\u2019s\nopposition.\nSituation Getting Worse.\nJapan\u2019s situation was getting\nworse daily, however, and on June\n28 Premier Admiral Kantaro Suzuki\ncalled a meeting of all the elder\nstatesmen, including all former\nPremiers, at which he reported indi\ncations that Russia would join the\nwar.\nThe meeting decided to instruct\nAmbassador Naotake Sato in Mos\ncow to pay special attention to\nRussia\u2019s attitude. Meantime, the\ngovernment prepared peace pro\nposals for submission through Mos\ncow to the Big Three at Potsdam.\nThese finally were forwarded to\nPremier Stalin in Emperor Hiro\nhito\u2019s name.\nJapanese Army leaders, meantime,\nsplit on whether to surrender, but\nboth sides wanted the Emperor to\ntake the reins of government. This\ndesire became a demand after\nJapan\u2019s fleet was wiped out as a\nfighting force on July 18.\nThe Empress Nagako was sent to\nseek advice of the dowager empress\nand on her return it was decided to\nform a commission to decide def\ninitely on the question of continuing\nthe war or surrendering.\n21 on Commission.\nThe commission consisted of 21\npersons, including the Imperial\nPrinces Chichibu and Takamatsu\nand leading army and navy officers.\nThis commission decided Japan\nwould surrender, provided that the\nEmperor retained his sovereignty,\nthat Japan kept Formosa and Korea\nand that Japan retained her army\nand navy, subject to Allied restric\ntions. As a fourth condition, it pro\nposed that those responsible for the\nwar would commit suicide and the\nAllies would drop war criminal\ncharges.\nBefore these conditions could be\nplaced before the Allies the Pots\ndam ultimatum was announced.\nAfter the Americans dropped the\nfirst atomic bomb on Hiroshima and\nJapan lost a possible mediator\nthrough Russia\u2019s declaration of war,\nthe Japanese Peace Commission held\nan emergency meeting which lasted\nthroughout the night of August 8.\nThis meeting, the newspaper said,\nproduced Japan\u2019s offer to surrender\non the Potsdam terms, provided the\nEmperor could be retained.\n3 I\nFLIGHTS DAILY I\nCHICAGO!\nDirect, short route\nA'A hours\nLeave 5:00, 7:00, 10:00 pm\nOnly one stop\u2014Toledo\nUNITED\nAIR LINES\nCaB Republic 3636\nK Street between 15th end 16th\nin Hotel Stetler\n666\u201415th St.. N. W.\nAcid Indigestion\nRelieved in 5 minutes or\ndouble your money beck\nWhen excess stomach Kid causes painful, suffers!\ning gas. sour stomach aid heartburn, doctors usually\nprescribe the fastest-acting medicines known for\nlymptomatlc relief\u2014medicines like those in Bell-ana\nTablets. No laxative. Bell-ana brings comfort in a\nUffy or double your money back oo return of bottle\nus. 2So at all druggists.\nSAMPLE STEEL BLDG.\nFor Sole\u201416x32 Ft.\nNo floor, canvas sides, suitable for\ngarage, barn, roadside stand.\nBARGAIN\nLocated at 5100 Wise. Ave.\nWood lay 9662\nKODAK FILM\nDeveloped and A BW\nPrinted. Any Sixe 6\nor 8 Exp. Roll_\nWeaco Rotary (Chrome)\nPrint Dryers\nProfession! Model 0/1 Q 2\n24x28 Drying Surface.\nn ITT CAMERA\nM I Ai CENTERS\n1112 G St. N.W.\nNew SUrc Hoars, 0:30 to 0\n\u201cKeep Rollin' with Nolan\"\nNOLAN\nAUTOMOBILE\nLOANS\nFavorable Rates\nNo Indorsers\n1102 New York Ave. N.W.\nGreyhound Bus Termiasl\nRE. 1200\nOpeo Till 6 P.M.\nHay Fever\nSufferers\nObtain Relief of 1\nSymptons with j\nHayrin Nasal Filters\nCall or Write for\nDescriptive Circular\nPrice\n$5.00\nComplete\nGibson's\n917 G St N.W.\nUNITED M\ngsL TASTES JSSS.\ngr V C vj\nEven PROVIDENCE folk, 1\nI traditionally proud of jf\n8 their special mincemeat 1\nI recipe, have joined other 1\nLafayette diners in ap- 1\nproving our home made I\ndesserts.\nI DINNER SPECIALS I\nStart at $1.50 ^k\nFeaturing Home Mads\n^B Desserts Daily i^B\nB With Softly-Toned, B\nB Softly-Lighted B\nCOCKTAIL LOUNGE\nI HOTEL LAFAYETTE I\n16th A Ere Sts. N.W. 8\nAir Co